# Exploratory Data Analysis

```{r}
# Missingness
colSums(is.na(flights_train[, c("dep_del15", "dep_time", "crs_dep_time")]))

flights_train |>
  summarise(across(everything(), ~mean(is.na(.)))) |>
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "variable", values_to = "pct_missing") |>
  filter(pct_missing > 0) |>
  arrange(desc(pct_missing)) |>
  print(n = 30)
```

Most missingness is in the delay-reason columns (carrier delay, weather delay, etc.) which we can't use for prediction anyway. Worth checking whether any pre-departure features we plan to use have meaningful missingness.

```{r}
# Target distribution
flights_train |>
  count(dep_del15)

flights_train |>
  ggplot(aes(x = dep_del15)) +
  geom_bar()
```

Classes are roughly 80/20 on-time vs. delayed. Defaulting to a 0.5 threshold will bias toward predicting on-time, but since AUC is our metric this matters less for model selection.

```{r}
# Delay rate by carrier
flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(op_unique_carrier) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), n = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  arrange(desc(delay_rate)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(op_unique_carrier, delay_rate), y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "carrier", y = "proportion delayed >= 15 min")
```

Meaningful variation across carriers — carrier should be a useful predictor. Carriers with few flights at PIT will have noisy estimates, so consider smoothing or grouping them.

```{r}
# Delay rate by departure time
flights_train |>
  ggplot(aes(x = dep_time)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 40)

flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15), !is.na(sched_dep_hour)) |>
  group_by(sched_dep_hour) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = sched_dep_hour, y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point()
```

Delays increase steadily through the day and peak in the evening — the classic delay cascade where a late plane from an earlier leg ripples forward. Early morning flights are most punctual since planes are freshly repositioned overnight. `sched_dep_hour` should be a strong feature.

```{r}
# Delay rate by carrier (stacked bar)
flights_train |>
  ggplot(aes(x = op_unique_carrier, fill = factor(dep_del15))) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  coord_flip()

# Delay rate by month
flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(month) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = delay_rate, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point()

# Delay rate by day of week
flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(day_of_week) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week, y = delay_rate, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point()
```

Delays peak in summer (June–August) and December, consistent with high-traffic periods and weather. Day-of-week effect is more modest — Thursdays/Fridays tend to be slightly worse, Saturdays most punctual.

```{r}
# Top destinations
flights_train |>
  count(dest, sort = TRUE) |>
  slice_head(n = 15)
```

Dominant routes are major hubs (ORD, ATL, CLT, etc.) which makes sense for a mid-size airport. Hub routes are more exposed to system-wide delays — route-level delay rates could be a useful engineered feature.
